{{Chinese |pic=Francis Lister Hawks Pott.jpg |t=卜舫濟 |s=卜舫济 |p=Bŭ Fǎngjì |w=Pu Fang-chi |mi={{IPAc-cmn|p|u|3|-|f|ang|3|j|i|4}} |wuu = poʔ³fɑ̃⁴⁴tɕi²¹}} '''Francis Lister Hawks Pott''' ({{zh|t=卜舫濟}}; February 22, 1864 – March 7, 1947) was an American Episcopal missionary and educator in China. He served as President of St. John's College (later renamed [[St. John's University, Shanghai|St. John's University]]), one of China's oldest and most prestigious universities, from 1888 until 1941. With the outbreak of the [[Pacific War]] in 1941 and the Japanese occupation of the [[Shanghai International Settlement]], he left for the United States. After World War II, he returned to Shanghai, but soon died in 1947.
Pott was married to Soo Ngoo Wong ({{zh|t=黃素娥|p=Huáng Sù'é}}), who died in 1918, and the father of Olivia H. Pott and Walter Graham Hawks Pott.
